        <handout margin="1in" bottom="1.25cm" xml:id="Week2Mon">
            <title>Monday Week 2 - Vertical Stretches and Compressions</title>
<page>
        <objectives>
          <ul>
            <li>Introduce vertical stretches and compressions.</li>
            <li>Practice working with the graphical transformations we have learned so far..</li>
          </ul>
        </objectives>
            <introduction>
                <p>
                    On Friday we introduced graphical transformations. Today, we will discuss transformations arising from multiplying a function by a constant.
                </p>
            </introduction>



<example>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Use the graph of <m>y = f(x)</m> given below, and the labeled points on the graphs, to sketch graphs of
    <ol>
        <li>
            <p>
                <m>y = \frac{1}{2}f(x)</m> and
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                <m>y=2f(x)</m>.
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
</p>
    <image>
<prefigure label = "vert_stretch_cubic" xmlns="https://prefigure.org">
<diagram dimensions="(500,500)" margins="(100,0,100,5)">
  <definition>f(x)=(7*x^3)/30-x^2/2+x/15+4</definition>
  <coordinates bbox="(-8,-6,8,10)">
    <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y" spacings="(-8,1,8),(-6,1,10)"/>
    <graph at="graph" function="f"/>
    <point  p="(0,f(0))" alignment="w">
      <m>(0,4)</m>
    </point>
    <point  p="(-2,f(-2))" alignment="ne">
      <m>(-2,0)</m>
    </point>
    <point p="(2,f(2))" alignment="ne">
      <m>(2,4)</m>
    </point>
    <point p="(3,f(3))" alignment="ne">
      <m>(3,6)</m>
    </point>
  </coordinates>
</diagram>
</prefigure>
</image>  

</statement>
</example>
    
<p>
To summarize:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        <p>
        <m>f(-x)</m> has the same graph as <m>f(x)</m>, except <fillin characters="35" /> <fillin characters="25" />.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
        <m>-f(x)</m> has the same graph as <m>f(x)</m>, except <fillin characters="35" /> <fillin characters="25" />.
        </p>
    </li>   
</ul>

</page>
